# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: networking
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] The **Address Resolution Protocol** (**ARP**) is a communication protocol for discovering the link layer address, such as a MAC address, associated with an internet layer address, typically an IPv4 address.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] The protocol, part of the Internet protocol suite, was defined in 1982 by RFC 826, which is Internet Standard STD 37.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] ARP enables a host to send, for example, an IPv4 packet to another node in the local network by providing a protocol to get the MAC address associated with an IP address.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] The host broadcasts a request containing the target node's IP address, and the node with that IP address replies with its MAC address.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] ARP has been implemented with many combinations of network and data link layer technologies, such as IPv4, Chaosnet, DECnet and Xerox PARC Universal Packet (PUP) using IEEE 802 standards, FDDI, X.25, Frame Relay and Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM).
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] In Internet Protocol Version 6 (IPv6) networks, the functionality of ARP is provided by the Neighbor Discovery Protocol (NDP).
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] The Address Resolution Protocol is a request–response protocol.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] Its messages are directly encapsulated by a link-layer protocol.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] It is communicated within the boundaries of a single subnetwork and is never routed.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] The Address Resolution Protocol uses a simple message format containing one address resolution request or response.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] The packets are carried at the data link layer of the underlying network as raw payload.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] In the case of Ethernet, a 0x0806 EtherType value is used to identify ARP frames.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] The size of the ARP message depends on the link layer and network layer address sizes.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] The message header specifies the types of network in use at each layer as well as the size of addresses of each.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] The message header is completed with the operation code for request (1) and reply (2).
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] The payload of the packet consists of four addresses: the hardware and protocol addresses of the sender and receiver hosts.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] The principal packet structure of ARP packets is shown in the following table, which illustrates the case of IPv4 networks running on Ethernet.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] In this scenario, the packet has 48-bit fields for the sender hardware address (SHA) and target hardware address (THA), and 32-bit fields for the corresponding sender and target protocol addresses (SPA and TPA).
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] The ARP packet size in this case is 28 bytes.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] This field specifies the network link protocol type.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] This field specifies the internetwork protocol for which the ARP request is intended.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] Length (in octets) of internetwork addresses.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] The internetwork protocol is specified in PTYPE.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] Specifies the operation that the sender is performing: 1 for request, 2 for reply.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] In an ARP request, this field is used to indicate the address of the host sending the request.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] In an ARP reply, this field is used to indicate the address of the host that the request was looking for.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] In an ARP request, this field is ignored.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] In an ARP reply this field is used to indicate the address of the host that originated the ARP request.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] Internetwork address of the intended receiver.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] ARP parameter values have been standardized and are maintained by the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA).
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] This appears in the Ethernet frame header when the payload is an ARP packet and is not to be confused with PTYPE, which appears within this encapsulated ARP packet.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] ARP's placement within the Internet protocol suite and the OSI model may be a matter of confusion or even of dispute.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] RFC 826 places it into the link layer and characterizes it as a tool to inquire about the "higher level layer", such as the Internet layer.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] RFC 1122 also discusses ARP in its link layer section.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] Richard Stevens places ARP in the OSI's data link layer while newer editions associate it with the network layer or introduce an intermediate OSI layer 2.5.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] Two computers, *A* and *B*, are connected to the same local area network with no intervening gateway or router.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] *A* has a packet to send to IP address *192.168.0.55* which happens to be the address of *B*.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] Before sending the packet to *B*, *A* broadcasts an ARP request message – addressed with the broadcast MAC address *FF:FF:FF:FF:FF:FF* and requesting response from the node with IP address *192.168.0.55*.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] All nodes of the network receive the message, but only *B* replies since it has the requested IP address.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] *B* responds with an ARP response message containing its MAC addresses which *A* receives.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] *A* sends the data packet on the link addressed with *B*'s MAC address.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] Typically, a network node maintains a lookup cache that associates IP and MAC addresses.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] In this example, if *A* had the lookup cached, then it would not need to broadcast the ARP request.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] Also, when *B* received the request, it could cache the lookup to *A* so that if *B* needs to send a packet to *A* later, it does not need to use ARP to look up its MAC address.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] Finally, when *A* receives the ARP response, it can cache the lookup for future messages addressed to the same IP address.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] An **ARP probe** in IPv4 is an ARP request constructed with the SHA of the probing host, an SPA of all 0s, a THA of all 0s, and a TPA set to the IPv4 address being probed for.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] If some host on the network regards the IPv4 address (in the TPA) as its own, it will reply to the probe (via the SHA of the probing host) thus informing the probing host of the address conflict.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] If instead there is no host that regards the IPv4 address as its own, then there will be no reply.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] When several such probes have been sent, with slight delays, and none receive replies, it can reasonably be expected that no conflict exists.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] As the original probe packet contains neither a valid SHA/SPA nor a valid THA/TPA pair, there is no risk of any host using the packet to update its cache with problematic data.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] Before beginning to use an IPv4 address (whether received from manual configuration, DHCP, or some other means), a host implementing this specification must test to see if the address is already in use, by broadcasting ARP probe packets.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] ARP may also be used as a simple announcement protocol.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] This is useful for updating other hosts' mappings of a hardware address when the sender's IP address or MAC address changes.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] Such an announcement, also called a **gratuitous ARP** (**GARP**) message, is usually broadcast as an *ARP request* containing the SPA in the target field (TPA=SPA), with THA set to zero.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] An alternative way is to broadcast an *ARP reply* with the sender's SHA and SPA duplicated in the target fields (TPA=SPA, THA=SHA).
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] The *ARP request* and *ARP reply* announcements are both standards-based methods, but the *ARP request* method is preferred.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] Some devices may be configured for the use of either of these two types of announcements.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] An ARP announcement is not intended to solicit a reply; instead, it updates any cached entries in the ARP tables of other hosts that receive the packet.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] The operation code in the announcement may be either request or reply; the ARP standard specifies that the opcode is only processed after the ARP table has been updated from the address fields.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] Many operating systems issue an ARP announcement during startup.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] This helps to resolve problems that would otherwise occur if, for example, a network card was recently changed (changing the IP-address-to-MAC-address mapping) and other hosts still have the old mapping in their ARP caches.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] ARP announcements are also used by some network interfaces to provide load balancing for incoming traffic.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] In a team of network cards, it is used to announce a different MAC address within the team that should receive incoming packets.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] ARP announcements can be used in the Zeroconf protocol to allow automatic assignment of a link-local address to an interface where no other IP address configuration is available.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] The announcements are used to ensure an address chosen by a host is not in use by other hosts on the network link.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] InARP is primarily used in Frame Relay (DLCI) and ATM networks, in which layer-2 addresses of virtual circuits are sometimes obtained from layer-2 signaling, and the corresponding layer-3 addresses must be available before those virtual circuits can be used.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] The Reverse Address Resolution Protocol (Reverse ARP or RARP), like InARP, translates layer-2 addresses to layer-3 addresses.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] However, in InARP, the requesting station queries the layer-3 address of another node, whereas RARP is used to obtain the layer-3 address of the requesting station itself for address configuration purposes.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] RARP is obsolete; it was replaced by BOOTP, which was later superseded by the Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP).
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] Because ARP does not provide methods for authenticating ARP replies on a network, ARP replies can come from systems other than the one with the required Layer 2 address.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] An ARP *proxy* is a system that answers the ARP request on behalf of another system for which it will forward traffic, normally as a part of the network's design, such as for a dial-up internet service.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] By contrast, in ARP *spoofing* the answering system, or *spoofer*, replies to a request for another system's address with the aim of intercepting data bound for that system.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] A malicious user may use ARP spoofing to perform a man-in-the-middle or denial-of-service attack on other users on the network.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] Various software exists to both detect and perform ARP spoofing attacks, though ARP itself does not provide any methods of protection from such attacks.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] Computers may maintain lists of known addresses, rather than using an active protocol.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] In this method, each computer maintains a database of the mapping of Layer 3 addresses (e.g., IP addresses) to Layer 2 addresses (e.g., Ethernet MAC addresses).
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] This data is maintained primarily by interpreting ARP packets from the local network link.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] Thus, it is often called the *ARP cache*.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] Since at least the 1980s, networked computers have a utility called *arp* for interrogating or manipulating this database.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] Historically, other methods were used to maintain the mapping between addresses, such as static configuration files, or centrally maintained lists.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] Embedded systems such as networked cameras and networked power distribution devices, which lack a user interface, can use so-called *ARP stuffing* to make an initial network connection, although this is a misnomer, as ARP is not involved.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] The computer sends special packets to the device, typically a ping packet with a non-default size.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] The user then communicates with it by telnet or web protocols to complete the configuration.
[src:networking/address-resolution-protocol] Such devices typically have a method to disable this process once the device is operating normally, as the capability can make it vulnerable to attack.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The **Domain Name System** (**DNS**) is a hierarchical and distributed name service that provides a naming system for computers, services, and other resources on the Internet or other Internet Protocol (IP) networks.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] It associates various information with *domain names* (identification strings) assigned to each of the associated entities.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Most prominently, it translates readily memorized domain names to the numerical IP addresses needed for locating and identifying computer services and devices with the underlying network protocols.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System has been an essential component of the functionality of the Internet since 1985.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System delegates the responsibility of assigning domain names and mapping those names to Internet resources by designating authoritative name servers for each domain.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Network administrators may delegate authority over subdomains of their allocated name space to other name servers.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] This mechanism provides distributed and fault-tolerant service and was designed to avoid a single large central database.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] In addition, the DNS specifies the technical functionality of the database service that is at its core.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] It defines the DNS protocol, a detailed specification of the data structures and data communication exchanges used in the DNS, as part of the Internet protocol suite.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The Internet maintains two principal namespaces, the domain name hierarchy and the IP address spaces.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System maintains the domain name hierarchy and provides translation services between it and the address spaces.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Internet name servers and a communication protocol implement the Domain Name System.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] A DNS name server is a server that stores the DNS records for a domain; a DNS name server responds with answers to queries against its database.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The most common types of records stored in the DNS database are for start of authority (SOA), IP addresses (A and AAAA), SMTP mail exchangers (MX), name servers (NS), pointers for reverse DNS lookups (PTR), and domain name aliases (CNAME).
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Although not intended to be a general-purpose database, DNS has been expanded over time to store records for other types of data for either automatic lookups, such as DNSSEC records, or for human queries such as *responsible person* (RP) records.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] As a general-purpose database, the DNS has also been used in combating unsolicited email (spam) by storing blocklists.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The DNS database is conventionally stored in a structured text file, the zone file, but other database systems are common.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System originally used the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) as transport over IP.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Reliability, security, and privacy concerns spawned the use of the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) as well as numerous other protocol developments.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] An often-used analogy to explain the DNS is that it serves as the phone book for the Internet by translating human-friendly computer hostnames into IP addresses.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The DNS can be quickly and transparently updated, allowing a service's location on the network to change without affecting the end users, who continue to use the same hostname.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Users take advantage of this when they use meaningful Uniform Resource Locators (URLs) and e-mail addresses without having to know how the computer actually locates the services.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] An important and ubiquitous function of the DNS is its central role in distributed Internet services such as cloud services and content delivery networks.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] When a user accesses a distributed Internet service using a URL, the domain name of the URL is translated to the IP address of a server that is proximal to the user.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The key functionality of the DNS exploited here is that different users can *simultaneously* receive different translations for the *same* domain name, a key point of divergence from a traditional phone-book view of the DNS.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] This process of using the DNS to assign proximal servers to users is key to providing faster and more reliable responses on the Internet and is widely used by most major Internet services.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The DNS reflects the structure of administrative responsibility on the Internet.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Each subdomain is a zone of administrative autonomy delegated to a manager.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] For zones operated by a registry, administrative information is often complemented by the registry's RDAP and WHOIS services.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] That data can be used to gain insight on, and track responsibility for, a given host on the Internet.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Using a simpler, more memorable name in place of a host's numerical address dates back to the ARPANET era.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The Stanford Research Institute (now SRI International) maintained a text file named HOSTS.TXT that mapped host names to the numerical addresses of computers on the ARPANET.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Elizabeth Feinler developed and maintained the first ARPANET directory.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Maintenance of numerical addresses, called the Assigned Numbers List, was handled by Jon Postel at the University of Southern California's Information Sciences Institute (ISI), whose team worked closely with SRI.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Computers, including their hostnames and addresses, were added to the primary file by contacting the SRI Network Information Center (NIC), directed by Feinler, via telephone during business hours.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Later, Feinler set up a WHOIS directory on a server in the NIC for retrieval of information about resources, contacts, and entities.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] She and her team developed the concept of domains.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Feinler suggested that domains should be based on the location of the physical address of the computer.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Computers at educational institutions would have the domain *edu*, for example.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] She and her team managed the Host Naming Registry from 1972 to 1989.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] By the early 1980s, maintaining a single, centralized host table had become slow and unwieldy and the emerging network required an automated naming system to address technical and personnel issues.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Postel directed the task of forging a compromise between five competing proposals of solutions to Paul Mockapetris.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Mockapetris instead created the Domain Name System in 1983 while at the University of Southern California.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The Internet Engineering Task Force published the original specifications in RFC 882 and RFC 883 in November 1983.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] These were updated in RFC 973 in January 1986.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] In 1984, four UC Berkeley students, Douglas Terry, Mark Painter, David Riggle, and Songnian Zhou, wrote the first Unix name server implementation for the Berkeley Internet Name Domain, commonly referred to as BIND.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] In 1985, Kevin Dunlap of DEC substantially revised the DNS implementation.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Mike Karels, Phil Almquist, and Paul Vixie then took over BIND maintenance.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Internet Systems Consortium was founded in 1994 by Rick Adams, Paul Vixie, and Carl Malamud, expressly to provide a home for BIND development and maintenance.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] BIND versions from 4.9.3 onward were developed and maintained by ISC, with support provided by ISC's sponsors.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] As co-architects/programmers, Bob Halley and Paul Vixie released the first production-ready version of BIND version 8 in May 1997.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Since 2000, over 43 different core developers have worked on BIND.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] In November 1987, RFC 1034 and RFC 1035 superseded the 1983 DNS specifications.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Several additional Request for Comments have proposed extensions to the core DNS protocols.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The domain name space consists of a tree data structure.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Each node or leaf in the tree has a *label* and zero or more *resource records* (RR), which hold information associated with the domain name.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The domain name itself consists of the label, concatenated with the name of its parent node on the right, separated by a dot.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The tree sub-divides into *zones* beginning at the root zone.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] A DNS zone may consist of as many domains and subdomains as the zone manager chooses.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] DNS can also be partitioned according to *class* where the separate classes can be thought of as an array of parallel namespace trees.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Administrative responsibility for any zone may be divided by creating additional zones.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Authority over the new zone is said to be *delegated* to a designated name server.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The parent zone ceases to be authoritative for the new zone.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The definitive descriptions of the rules for forming domain names appear in RFC 1035, RFC 1123, RFC 2181, and RFC 5892.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] A domain name consists of one or more parts, technically called *labels*, that are conventionally concatenated, and delimited by dots, such as example.com.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The right-most label conveys the top-level domain; for example, the domain name www.example.com belongs to the top-level domain *com*.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The hierarchy of domains descends from right to left; each label to the left specifies a subdivision, or subdomain of the domain to the right.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] For example, the label *example* specifies a subdomain of the *com* domain, and *www* is a subdomain of example.com.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] This tree of subdivisions may have up to 127 levels.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] A label may contain zero to 63 characters, because the length is only allowed to take 6 bits.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The null label of length zero is reserved for the root zone.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The full domain name may not exceed the length of 253 characters in its textual representation (or 254 with the trailing dot).
[src:networking/domain-name-system] In the internal binary representation of the DNS this maximum length of 253 requires 255 octets of storage, as it also stores the length of the first of many labels and adds last null byte.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] 255 length is only achieved with at least 6 labels (counting the last null label).
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Although no technical limitation exists to prevent domain name labels from using any character that is representable by an octet, hostnames use a preferred format and character set.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The characters allowed in labels are a subset of the ASCII character set, consisting of characters *a* through *z*, *A* through *Z*, digits *0* through *9*, and hyphen.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] This rule is known as the *LDH rule* (letters, digits, hyphen).
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Domain names are interpreted in a case-independent manner.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Labels may not start or end with a hyphen.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] An additional rule requires that top-level domain names should not be all-numeric.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The limited set of ASCII characters permitted in the DNS prevented the representation of names and words of many languages in their native alphabets or scripts.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] To make this possible, ICANN approved the Internationalizing Domain Names in Applications (IDNA) system, by which user applications, such as web browsers, map Unicode strings into the valid DNS character set using Punycode.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] In 2009, ICANN approved the installation of internationalized domain name country code top-level domains (*ccTLD*s).
[src:networking/domain-name-system] In addition, many registries of the existing top-level domain names (*TLD*s) have adopted the IDNA system, guided by RFC 5890, RFC 5891, RFC 5892, RFC 5893.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System is maintained by a distributed database system, which uses the client–server model.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The nodes of this database are the name servers.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Each domain has at least one authoritative DNS server that publishes information about that domain and the name servers of any domains subordinate to it.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The top of the hierarchy is served by the root name servers, the servers to query when looking up (*resolving*) a TLD.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] An authoritative name server can either be a *primary* server or a *secondary* server.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Historically the terms *master/slave* and *primary/secondary* were sometimes used interchangeably but the current practice is to use the latter form.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] A primary server is a server that stores the original copies of all zone records.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] A secondary server uses a special automatic updating mechanism in the DNS protocol in communication with its primary to maintain an identical copy of the primary records.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Every DNS zone must be assigned a set of authoritative name servers.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] This set of servers is stored in the parent domain zone with name server (NS) records.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] An authoritative server indicates its status of supplying definitive answers, deemed *authoritative*, by setting a protocol flag, called the "*Authoritative Answer*" (*AA*) bit in its responses.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] When a name server is designated as the authoritative server for a domain name for which it does not have authoritative data, it presents a type of error called a "lame delegation" or "lame response".
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Domain name resolvers determine the domain name servers responsible for the domain name in question by a sequence of queries starting with the right-most (top-level) domain label.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] For proper operation of its domain name resolver, a network host is configured with an initial cache (*hints*) of the known addresses of the root name servers.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The hints are updated periodically by an administrator by retrieving a dataset from a reliable source.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Assuming the resolver has no cached records to accelerate the process, the resolution process starts with a query to one of the root servers.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] In typical operation, the root servers do not answer directly, but respond with a referral to more authoritative servers, e.g., a query for "www.wikipedia.org" is referred to the *org* servers.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The resolver now queries the servers referred to, and iteratively repeats this process until it receives an authoritative answer.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The diagram illustrates this process for the host that is named by the fully qualified domain name "www.wikipedia.org".
[src:networking/domain-name-system] This mechanism would place a large traffic burden on the root servers, if every resolution on the Internet required starting at the root.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] In practice caching is used in DNS servers to off-load the root servers, and as a result, root name servers actually are involved in only a relatively small fraction of all requests.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] In theory, authoritative name servers are sufficient for the operation of the Internet.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] However, with only authoritative name servers operating, every DNS query must start with recursive queries at the root zone of the Domain Name System and each user system would have to implement resolver software capable of recursive operation.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Typically, such caching DNS servers also implement the recursive algorithm necessary to resolve a given name starting with the DNS root through to the authoritative name servers of the queried domain.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] With this function implemented in the name server, user applications gain efficiency in design and operation.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The combination of DNS caching and recursive functions in a name server is not mandatory; the functions can be implemented independently in servers for special purposes.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Internet service providers (ISP) typically provide recursive and caching name servers for their customers.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] In addition, many home networking routers implement DNS caches and recursion to improve efficiency in the local network.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The client side of the DNS is called a DNS resolver.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] A resolver is responsible for initiating and sequencing the queries that ultimately lead to a full resolution (translation) of the resource sought, e.g., translation of a domain name into an IP address.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] DNS resolvers are classified by a variety of query methods, such as *recursive*, *non-recursive*, and *iterative*.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] A resolution process may use a combination of these methods.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] In a *non-recursive query*, a DNS resolver queries a DNS server that provides a record either for which the server is authoritative, or it provides a partial result without querying other servers.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] In case of a caching DNS resolver, the non-recursive query of its local DNS cache delivers a result and reduces the load on upstream DNS servers by caching DNS resource records for a period of time after an initial response from upstream DNS servers.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] In a *recursive query*, a DNS resolver queries a single DNS server, which may in turn query other DNS servers on behalf of the requester.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] For example, a simple stub resolver running on a home router typically makes a recursive query to the DNS server run by the user's ISP.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] A recursive query is one for which the DNS server answers the query completely by querying other name servers as needed.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] In typical operation, a client issues a recursive query to a caching recursive DNS server, which subsequently issues non-recursive queries to determine the answer and send a single answer back to the client.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The resolver, or another DNS server acting recursively on behalf of the resolver, negotiates use of recursive service using bits in the query headers.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] DNS servers are not required to support recursive queries.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The *iterative query* procedure is a process in which a DNS resolver queries a chain of one or more DNS servers.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Each server refers the client to the next server in the chain, until the current server can fully resolve the request.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] For example, a possible resolution of www.example.com would query a global root server, then a "com" server, and finally an "example.com" server.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Name servers in delegations are identified by name, rather than by IP address.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] This means that a resolving name server must issue another DNS request to discover the IP address of the server to which it has been referred.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] If the name given in the delegation is a subdomain of the domain for which the delegation is being provided, there is a circular dependency.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] In this case, the name server providing the delegation must also provide one or more IP addresses for the authoritative name server mentioned in the delegation.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The delegating name server provides this glue in the form of records in the *additional section* of the DNS response, and provides the delegation in the *authority section* of the response.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] A glue record is a combination of the name server and IP address.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] For example, if the authoritative name server for example.org is ns1.example.org, a computer trying to resolve www.example.org first resolves ns1.example.org.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] As ns1 is contained in example.org, this requires resolving example.org first, which presents a circular dependency.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] To break the dependency, the name server for the top level domain org includes glue along with the delegation for example.org.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The glue records are address records that provide IP addresses for ns1.example.org.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The resolver uses one or more of these IP addresses to query one of the domain's authoritative servers, which allows it to complete the DNS query.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] A common approach to reduce the query load on DNS servers is to cache the results of name resolution locally or on intermediary resolver hosts.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Each DNS query result comes with a time to live (TTL), which indicates how long the information remains valid before it needs to be discarded or refreshed.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] This TTL is determined by the administrator of the authoritative DNS server and can range from a few seconds to several days or even weeks.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] As a result of this distributed caching architecture, changes to DNS records do not propagate throughout the network immediately, but require all caches to expire and to be refreshed after the TTL.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] RFC 1912 conveys basic rules for determining appropriate TTL values.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Some resolvers may override TTL values, as the protocol supports caching for up to sixty-eight years or no caching at all.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Negative caching, i.e. the caching of the fact of non-existence of a record, is determined by name servers authoritative for a zone which must include the Start of Authority (SOA) record when reporting no data of the requested type exists.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The value of the *minimum* field of the SOA record and the TTL of the SOA itself is used to establish the TTL for the negative answer.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] A reverse DNS lookup is a query of the DNS for domain names when the IP address is known.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Multiple domain names may be associated with an IP address.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The DNS stores IP addresses in the form of domain names as specially formatted names in pointer (PTR) records within the infrastructure top-level domain arpa.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] For IPv6, the reverse lookup domain is ip6.arpa.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The IP address is represented as a name in reverse-ordered octet representation for IPv4, and reverse-ordered nibble representation for IPv6.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] When performing a reverse lookup, the DNS client converts the address into these formats before querying the name for a PTR record following the delegation chain as for any DNS query.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] For example, assuming the IPv4 address 208.80.152.2 is assigned to Wikimedia, it is represented as a DNS name in reverse order: 2.152.80.208.in-addr.arpa.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] When the DNS resolver gets a pointer (PTR) request, it begins by querying the root servers, which point to the servers of American Registry for Internet Numbers (ARIN) for the 208.in-addr.arpa zone.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] ARIN's servers delegate 152.80.208.in-addr.arpa to Wikimedia to which the resolver sends another query for 2.152.80.208.in-addr.arpa, which results in an authoritative response.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Users generally do not communicate directly with a DNS resolver.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Instead DNS resolution takes place transparently in applications such as web browsers, e-mail clients, and other Internet applications.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] When an application makes a request that requires a domain name lookup, such programs send a resolution request to the DNS resolver in the local operating system, which in turn handles the communications required.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The DNS resolver will almost invariably have a cache (see above) containing recent lookups.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] If the cache can provide the answer to the request, the resolver will return the value in the cache to the program that made the request.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] If the cache does not contain the answer, the resolver will send the request to one or more designated DNS servers.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] In any event, the name server thus queried will follow the process outlined above, until it either successfully finds a result or does not.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] It then returns its results to the DNS resolver; assuming it has found a result, the resolver duly caches that result for future use, and hands the result back to the software which initiated the request.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Some large ISPs have configured their DNS servers to violate rules, such as by disobeying TTLs, or by indicating that a domain name does not exist just because one of its name servers does not respond.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Some applications such as web browsers maintain an internal DNS cache to avoid repeated lookups via the network.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] This practice can add extra difficulty when debugging DNS issues as it obscures the history of such data.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] These caches typically use very short caching times on the order of one minute.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Internet Explorer represents a notable exception: versions up to IE 3.x cache DNS records for 24 hours by default.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Internet Explorer 4.x and later versions (up to IE 8) decrease the default timeout value to half an hour, which may be changed by modifying the default configuration.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] When Google Chrome detects issues with the DNS server it displays a specific error message.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System includes several other functions and features.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Hostnames and IP addresses are not required to match in a one-to-one relationship.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Multiple hostnames may correspond to a single IP address, which is useful in virtual hosting, in which many web sites are served from a single host.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Alternatively, a single hostname may resolve to many IP addresses to facilitate fault tolerance and load distribution to multiple server instances across an enterprise or the global Internet.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] DNS serves other purposes in addition to translating names to IP addresses.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] For instance, mail transfer agents use DNS to find the best mail server to deliver e-mail: An MX record provides a mapping between a domain and a mail exchanger; this can provide an additional layer of fault tolerance and load distribution.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The DNS is used for efficient storage and distribution of IP addresses of block-listed email hosts.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] A common method is to place the IP address of the subject host into the sub-domain of a higher level domain name, and to resolve that name to a record that indicates a positive or a negative indication.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] E-mail servers can query blocklist.example to find out if a specific host connecting to them is in the block list.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Many such block lists, either subscription-based or free of cost, are available for use by email administrators and anti-spam software.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] To provide resilience in the event of computer or network failure, multiple DNS servers are usually provided for coverage of each domain.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] At the top level of global DNS, thirteen groups of root name servers exist, with additional "copies" of them distributed worldwide via anycast addressing.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Dynamic DNS (DDNS) updates a DNS server with a client IP address on-the-fly, for example, when moving between ISPs or mobile hot spots, or when the IP address changes administratively.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The DNS protocol uses two types of DNS messages, queries and responses; both have the same format.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Each message consists of a header and four sections: question, answer, authority, and an additional space.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] A header field (*flags*) controls the content of these four sections.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The header section consists of the following fields: *Identification*, *Flags*, *Number of questions*, *Number of answers*, *Number of authority resource records* (RRs), and *Number of additional RRs*.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Each field is 16 bits long, and appears in the order given.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The identification field is used to match responses with queries.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] After the flags word, the header ends with four 16-bit integers which contain the number of records in each of the sections that follow, in the same order.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Indicates if the message is a query (0) or a reply (1).
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The type can be QUERY (standard query, 0), IQUERY (inverse query, 1), or STATUS (server status request, 2).
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Authoritative Answer, in a response, indicates if the DNS server is authoritative for the queried hostname.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] TrunCation, indicates that this message was truncated due to excessive length.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Recursion Desired, indicates if the client means a recursive query.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Recursion Available, in a response, indicates if the replying DNS server supports recursion.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Authentic Data, in a response, indicates if the replying DNS server verified the data.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Checking Disabled, in a query, indicates that non-verified data is acceptable in a response.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Response code, can be NOERROR (0), FORMERR (1, Format error), SERVFAIL (2), NXDOMAIN (3, Nonexistent domain), etc.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The question section has a simpler format than the resource record format used in the other sections.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The domain name is broken into discrete labels which are concatenated; each label is prefixed by the length of that label.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System specifies a database of information elements for network resources.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The types of information elements are categorized and organized with a list of DNS record types, the resource records (RRs).
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Each record has a type (name and number), an expiration time (time to live), a class, and type-specific data.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Resource records of the same type are described as a *resource record set* (RRset), having no special ordering.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] DNS resolvers return the entire set upon query, but servers may implement round-robin ordering to achieve load balancing.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] In contrast, the Domain Name System Security Extensions (DNSSEC) work on the complete set of resource record in canonical order.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The *CLASS* of a record is set to IN (for *Internet*) for common DNS records involving Internet hostnames, servers, or IP addresses.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] In addition, the classes Chaos (CH) and Hesiod (HS) exist.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Each class is an independent name space with potentially different delegations of DNS zones.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] In addition to resource records defined in a zone file, the domain name system also defines several request types that are used only in communication with other DNS nodes (*on the wire*), such as when performing zone transfers (AXFR/IXFR) or for EDNS (OPT).
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The domain name system supports wildcard DNS records which specify names that start with the *asterisk label*, `*`, e.g., `*.example`.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] DNS records belonging to wildcard domain names specify rules for generating resource records within a single DNS zone by substituting whole labels with matching components of the query name, including any specified descendants.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] For example, in the following configuration, the DNS zone *x.example* specifies that all subdomains, including subdomains of subdomains, of *x.example* use the mail exchanger (MX) *a.x.example*.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The AAAA record for *a.x.example* is needed to specify the mail exchanger IP address.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] As this has the result of excluding this domain name and its subdomains from the wildcard matches, an additional MX record for the subdomain *a.x.example*, as well as a wildcarded MX record for all of its subdomains, must also be defined in the DNS zone.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The role of wildcard records was refined in RFC 4592, because the original definition in RFC 1034 was incomplete and resulted in misinterpretations by implementers.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The original DNS protocol had limited provisions for extension with new features.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] In 1999, Paul Vixie published in RFC 2671 (superseded by RFC 6891) an extension mechanism, called Extension Mechanisms for DNS (EDNS) that introduced optional protocol elements without increasing overhead when not in use.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] This was accomplished through the OPT pseudo-resource record that only exists in wire transmissions of the protocol, but not in any zone files.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Initial extensions were also suggested (EDNS0), such as increasing the DNS message size in UDP datagrams.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Dynamic DNS updates use the UPDATE DNS opcode to add or remove resource records dynamically from a zone database maintained on an authoritative DNS server.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] This facility is useful to register network clients into the DNS when they boot or become otherwise available on the network.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] As a booting client may be assigned a different IP address each time from a DHCP server, it is not possible to provide static DNS assignments for such clients.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] From the time of its origin in 1983 the DNS has used the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) for transport over IP.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Its limitations have motivated numerous protocol developments for reliability, security, privacy, and other criteria, in the following decades.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] UDP reserves port number 53 for servers listening to queries.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Such a query consists of a clear-text request sent in a single UDP packet from the client, responded to with a clear-text reply sent in a single UDP packet from the server.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] When the length of the answer exceeds 512 bytes and both client and server support Extension Mechanisms for DNS (EDNS), larger UDP packets may be used.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Use of DNS over UDP is limited by, among other things, its lack of transport-layer encryption, authentication, reliable delivery, and message length.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] In 1989, RFC 1123 specified optional Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) transport for DNS queries, replies and, particularly, zone transfers.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Via fragmentation of long replies, TCP allows longer responses, reliable delivery, and re-use of long-lived connections between clients and servers.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] For larger responses, the server refers the client to TCP transport.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] DNS over TLS emerged as an IETF standard for encrypted DNS in 2016, utilizing Transport Layer Security (TLS) to protect the entire connection, rather than just the DNS payload.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] RFC 7858 specifies that opportunistic encryption and authenticated encryption may be supported, but did not make either server or client authentication mandatory.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] DNS over HTTPS was developed as a competing standard for DNS query transport in 2018, tunneling DNS query data over HTTPS, which transports HTTP over TLS.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] DoH was promoted as a more web-friendly alternative to DNS since, like DNSCrypt, it uses TCP port 443, and thus looks similar to web traffic, though they are easily differentiable in practice without proper padding.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] RFC 9250, published in 2022 by the Internet Engineering Task Force, describes DNS over QUIC.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] It has "privacy properties similar to DNS over TLS (DoT) [...], and latency characteristics similar to classic DNS over UDP".
[src:networking/domain-name-system] This method is not the same as DNS over HTTP/3.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] RFC 9953, published in 2026 by the Internet Engineering Task Force, describes DNS over CoAP.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The "application use case of DoC is inspired by DNS over HTTPS (DoH) (RFC 8484).
[src:networking/domain-name-system] However, DoC aims for deployment in the constrained Internet of Things (IoT), which usually conflicts with the requirements introduced by HTTPS." DoC outperforms other DNS resolution mechanisms in constrained scenarios.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Oblivious DNS (ODNS) was invented and implemented by researchers at Princeton University and the University of Chicago as an extension to unencrypted DNS, before DoH was standardized and widely deployed.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Apple and Cloudflare subsequently deployed the technology in the context of DoH, as Oblivious DoH (ODoH).
[src:networking/domain-name-system] ODoH combines ingress/egress separation (invented in ODNS) with DoH's HTTPS tunneling and TLS transport-layer encryption in a single protocol.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] DNS may be run over virtual private networks (VPNs) and tunneling protocols.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The privacy gains of Oblivious DNS can be garnered through the use of the preexisting Tor network of ingress and egress nodes, paired with the transport-layer encryption provided by TLS.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] DNSCrypt uses either TCP port 443, the same port as HTTPS encrypted web traffic, or UDP port 443.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] This introduced not only privacy regarding the content of the query, but also a significant measure of firewall-traversal capability.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Privacy of user/query pairs is created, since the ingress node does not know the content of the query, while the egress node does not know the identity of the client.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] DNSCrypt was first implemented in production by OpenDNS in December 2011.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] There are several free and open source software implementations that additionally integrate ODoH.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] It is available for a variety of operating systems, including Unix, Apple iOS, Linux, Android, and Windows.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Originally, security concerns were not major design considerations for DNS software or any software for deployment on the early Internet, as the network was not open for participation by the general public.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] However, the expansion of the Internet into the commercial sector in the 1990s changed the requirements for security measures to protect data integrity and user authentication.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Several vulnerability issues were discovered and exploited by malicious users.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] One such issue is DNS cache poisoning, in which data is distributed to caching resolvers under the pretense of being an authoritative origin server, thereby polluting the data store with potentially false information and long expiration times (time-to-live).
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Subsequently, legitimate application requests may be redirected to network hosts operated with malicious intent.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] DNS responses traditionally do not have a cryptographic signature, leading to many attack possibilities; the Domain Name System Security Extensions (DNSSEC) modify DNS to add support for cryptographically signed responses.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] DNSCurve has been proposed as an alternative to DNSSEC.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Other extensions, such as TSIG, add support for cryptographic authentication between trusted peers and are commonly used to authorize zone transfer or dynamic update operations.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Techniques such as forward-confirmed reverse DNS can also be used to help validate DNS results.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] DNS can also "leak" from otherwise secure or private connections, if attention is not paid to their configuration, and at times DNS has been used to bypass firewalls by malicious persons, and exfiltrate data, since it is often seen as innocuous.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Some domain names may be used to achieve spoofing effects.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] For example, paypal.com and paypa1.com are different names, yet users may be unable to distinguish them in a graphical user interface depending on the user's chosen typeface.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] In many fonts the letter *l* and the numeral *1* look very similar or even identical.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] This problem, known as the IDN homograph attack, is acute in systems that support internationalized domain names, as many character codes in ISO 10646 may appear identical on typical computer screens.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] This vulnerability is occasionally exploited in phishing.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] DNSMessenger is a type of cyber attack technique that uses the DNS to communicate and control malware remotely without relying on conventional protocols that might raise red flags.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The DNSMessenger attack is covert because DNS is primarily used for domain name resolution and is often not closely monitored by network security tools, making it an effective channel for attackers to exploit.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] This technique involves the use of DNS TXT records to send commands to infected systems.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Once malware has been surreptitiously installed on a victim's machine, it reaches out to a controlled domain to retrieve commands encoded in DNS text records.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] This form of malware communication is stealthy, as DNS requests are usually allowed through firewalls, and because DNS traffic is often seen as benign, these communications can bypass many network security defenses.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] DNSMessenger attacks can enable a wide array of malicious activities, from data exfiltration to the delivery of additional payloads, all while remaining under the radar of traditional network security measures.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Understanding and defending against such methods are crucial for maintaining robust cybersecurity.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Originally designed as a public, hierarchical, distributed and heavily cached database, the DNS protocol has no confidentiality controls.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] User queries and nameserver responses are sent unencrypted, enabling network packet sniffing, DNS hijacking, DNS cache poisoning and man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] This deficiency is commonly used by cybercriminals and network operators for marketing purposes, user authentication on captive portals and censorship.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] User privacy is further exposed by proposals for increasing the level of client IP information in DNS queries (RFC 7871) for the benefit of content delivery networks.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Solutions preventing DNS inspection by the local network operator have been criticized for thwarting corporate network security policies and Internet censorship.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Public DNS servers are also criticized for contributing to the centralization of the Internet by placing control over DNS resolution in the hands of the few large companies which can afford to run public resolvers.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The right to use a domain name is delegated by domain name registrars which are accredited by the Internet Corporation for Assigned Names and Numbers (ICANN) or other organizations such as OpenNIC, that are charged with overseeing the name and number systems of the Internet.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] In addition to ICANN, each top-level domain (TLD) is maintained and serviced technically by an administrative organization, operating a registry.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] A *registry* is responsible for operating the database of names within its authoritative zone, although the term is most often used for TLDs.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] A *registrant* is a person or organization who asked for domain registration.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The registry receives registration information from each domain name *registrar*, which is authorized (accredited) to assign names in the corresponding zone and publishes the information using the WHOIS protocol.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] As of 2015, usage of RDAP is being considered.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] ICANN publishes the complete list of TLDs, TLD registries, and domain name registrars.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Registrant information associated with domain names is maintained in an online database accessible with the WHOIS service.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] For most of the more than 290 country code top-level domains (ccTLDs), the domain registries maintain the WHOIS (Registrant, name servers, expiration dates, etc.) information.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] For instance, DENIC, Germany NIC, holds the DE domain data.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] From about 2001, most generic top-level domain (gTLD) registries have adopted this so-called *thick* registry approach, i.e. keeping the WHOIS data in central registries instead of registrar databases.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] For top-level domains on COM and NET, a *thin* registry model is used.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The domain registry (GoDaddy, BigRock and PDR, VeriSign, etc.) holds basic WHOIS data (i.e., registrar and name servers, etc.).
[src:networking/domain-name-system] On the other hand, organizations, i.e., registrants using ORG, are on the Public Interest Registry exclusively.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] Some domain name registries, often called *network information centers* (NIC), also function as registrars to end-users, in addition to providing access to the WHOIS datasets.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The top-level domain registries, such as for the domains COM, NET, and ORG use a registry-registrar model consisting of many domain name registrars.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] In this method of management, the registry only manages the domain name database and the relationship with the registrars.
[src:networking/domain-name-system] The *registrants* (users of a domain name) are customers of the registrar, in some cases through additional subcontracting of resellers.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The **Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol** (**DHCP**) is a network management protocol used on Internet Protocol (IP) networks for automatically assigning IP addresses and other communication parameters to devices connected to the network using a client–server architecture.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The technology eliminates the need for individually configuring network devices manually, and consists of two network components, a centrally installed network DHCP server and client instances of the protocol stack on each computer or device.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] When connected to the network, and periodically thereafter, a client requests a set of parameters from the server using DHCP.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] DHCP can be implemented on networks ranging in size from residential networks to large campus networks and regional ISP networks.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Many routers and residential gateways have DHCP server capability.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Most residential network routers receive a unique IP address within the ISP network.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Within a local network, a DHCP server assigns a local IP address to each device.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] DHCP services exist for networks running Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4), as well as version 6 (IPv6).
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The IPv6 version of the DHCP protocol is commonly called DHCPv6.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The Reverse Address Resolution Protocol (RARP) was defined in 1984 for the configuration of simple devices, such as diskless workstations, with a suitable IP address.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Acting in the data link layer, it made implementation difficult on many server platforms.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] It required that a server be present on each individual network link.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] RARP was superseded by the Bootstrap Protocol (BOOTP) defined in September 1985.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] This introduced the concept of a relay agent, which allowed the forwarding of BOOTP packets across networks, allowing one central BOOTP server to serve hosts on many IP subnets.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] It is based on BOOTP, but can dynamically allocate IP addresses from a pool and reclaim them when they are no longer in use.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] It can also be used to deliver a wide range of extra configuration parameters to IP clients, including platform-specific parameters.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Four years later, the DHCPINFORM message type (used for WPAD) and other small changes were added.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] This definition, from 1997, remains the core of the standard for IPv4 networks.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] After updates by many subsequent RFCs, its definition was replaced in 2018, where prefix delegation and stateless address autoconfiguration were now merged.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Internet Protocol (IP) defines how devices communicate within and across local networks on the Internet.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] A DHCP server can manage IP settings for devices on its local network, e.g., by assigning IP addresses to those devices automatically and dynamically.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] DHCP operates based on the client–server model.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] When a computer or other device connects to a network, the DHCP client software sends a DHCP broadcast query requesting the necessary information.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Any DHCP server on the network may service the request.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The DHCP server manages a pool of IP addresses and information about client configuration parameters such as default gateway, domain name, the name servers, and time servers.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] On receiving a DHCP request, the DHCP server may respond with specific information for each client, as previously configured by an administrator, or with a specific address and any other information valid for the entire network and for the time period for which the allocation (*lease*) is valid.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] A DHCP client typically queries this information immediately after booting, and periodically thereafter before the expiration of the information.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] When a DHCP client refreshes an assignment, it initially requests the same parameter values, but the DHCP server may assign a new address based on the assignment policies set by administrators.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] On large networks that consist of multiple links, a single DHCP server may service the entire network when aided by DHCP relay agents located on the interconnecting routers.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Such agents relay messages between DHCP clients and DHCP servers located on different subnets.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The request-and-grant process uses a lease concept with a controllable time period, allowing the DHCP server to reclaim and then reallocate IP addresses that are not renewed.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The DHCP server permanently assigns an IP address to a requesting client from a range defined by an administrator.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] This is like dynamic allocation, but the DHCP server keeps a table of past IP address assignments, so that it can preferentially assign to a client the same IP address that the client previously had.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] ) for each client to an IP address, which is offered to the requesting client.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] DHCP servers may be configured to fall back to other methods if this fails.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] DHCP services are used for Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4) and IPv6.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The details of the protocol for IPv4 and IPv6 differ sufficiently that they may be considered separate protocols.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] For the IPv6 operation, devices may alternatively use stateless address autoconfiguration.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] IPv6 hosts may also use link-local addressing to achieve operations restricted to the local network link.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The DHCP employs a connectionless service model, using the User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] It is implemented with two UDP port numbers for its operations which are the same as for the bootstrap protocol (BOOTP).
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The server listens on UDP port number 67, and the client listens on UDP port number 68.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] DHCP operations fall into four phases: server discovery, IP lease offer, IP lease request, and IP lease acknowledgement.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] These stages are often abbreviated as DORA for discovery, offer, request, and acknowledgement.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The DHCP operation begins with clients broadcasting a request.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] If the client and server are in different Broadcast Domains, a DHCP Helper or DHCP Relay Agent may be used.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Clients requesting renewal of an existing lease may communicate directly via UDP unicast, since the client already has an established IP address at that point.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Additionally, there is a BROADCAST flag (1 bit in 2 byte flags field, where all other bits are reserved and so are set to 0) the client can use to indicate in which way (broadcast or unicast) it can receive the DHCPOFFER: 0x8000 for broadcast, 0x0000 for unicast.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Usually, the DHCPOFFER is sent through unicast.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] For those hosts which cannot accept unicast packets before IP addresses are configured, this flag can be used to work around this issue.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The DHCP client broadcasts a DHCPDISCOVER message on the network subnet using the destination address *255.255.255.255* (limited broadcast) or the specific subnet broadcast address (directed broadcast).
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] A DHCP client may also request an IP address in the DHCPDISCOVER, which the server may take into account when selecting an address to offer.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] For example, if HTYPE is set to 1, to specify that the medium used is Ethernet, HLEN is set to 6 because an Ethernet address (MAC address) is 6 octets long.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The CHADDR is set to the MAC address used by the client.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] IPv4 packet, containing a UDP PDU with DHCP payload...
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] 192 octets of 0s, or overflow space for additional options; BOOTP legacy.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] When a DHCP server receives a DHCPDISCOVER message from a client, which is an IP address lease request, the DHCP server reserves an IP address for the client and makes a lease offer by sending a DHCPOFFER message to the client.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] This message may contain the client's *Client ID* (Option 61, containing a unique value, traditionally a MAC address), the IP address that the server is offering, the subnet mask, the lease duration, and the IP address of the DHCP server making the offer.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The DHCP server may also take notice of the hardware-level MAC address (as specified in the CHADDR field).
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] This field must be used to identify the client, if no Client ID is provided in the DHCP packet.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The DHCP server determines the configuration based on the client's hardware address as specified in the CHADDR (client hardware address) field.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] In the following example the server (*192.168.1.1*) specifies the client's IP address in the YIADDR (your IP address) field.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] In response to the DHCP offer, the client replies with a DHCPREQUEST message, broadcast to the server, requesting the offered address.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] A client can receive DHCP offers from multiple servers, but it will accept only one DHCP offer.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The client must send the *server identification* option in the DHCPREQUEST message, indicating the server whose offer the client has selected.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] When other DHCP servers receive this message, they withdraw any offers that they have made to the client and return their offered IP address to the pool of available addresses.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] When the DHCP server receives the DHCPREQUEST message from the client, the configuration process enters its final phase.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The acknowledgement phase involves sending a DHCPACK packet to the client.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] This packet includes the lease duration and any other configuration information that the client might have requested.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] At this point, the IP configuration process is completed.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The protocol expects the DHCP client to configure its network interface with the negotiated parameters.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] When the server is reusing an IP address from its pool, it may first check (using ping) to see if it is not taken already.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] This may happen if a host is configured manually with an IP address that lies within the DHCP scope.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Before claiming an IP address, the client should probe the newly received address (e.g. with ARP), in order to find if there is another host present in the network with the proposed IP address.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] If there is no reply, this address does not conflict with that of another host, so it is free to be used.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] If this probe finds another computer using that address, the client should broadcast a DHCPDECLINE to the DHCP server(s).
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] A DHCP client may request more information than the server sent with the original DHCPOFFER.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The client may also request repeat data for a particular application.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] For example, browsers use *DHCP Inform* to obtain web proxy settings via WPAD.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The client sends a request to the DHCP server to release the DHCP information and the client deactivates its IP address.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] As client devices usually do not know when users may unplug them from the network, the protocol does not mandate the sending of *DHCP Release*.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] A DHCP server can provide optional configuration parameters to the client.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] RFC 2132 describes the available DHCP options defined by Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA) - DHCP and BOOTP PARAMETERS.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] A DHCP client can select, manipulate and overwrite parameters provided by a DHCP server.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] In Unix-like systems this client-level refinement typically takes place according to the values in the configuration file */etc/dhclient.conf*.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Options are octet strings of varying length.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] This is called Type–length–value encoding.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The first octet is the option code, the second octet is the number of following octets and the remaining octets are code dependent.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] For example, the DHCP message-type option for an offer would appear as 0x35, 0x01, 0x02, where 0x35 is code 53 for "DHCP message type", 0x01 means one octet follows and 0x02 is the value of "offer".
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The following tables list the available DHCP options.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] This table lists the DHCP message types.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] These codes are the value in the DHCP extension 53, shown in the table above.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] An option exists to identify the vendor and functionality of a DHCP client.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The information is a variable-length string of characters or octets which has a meaning specified by the vendor of the DHCP client.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] One method by which a DHCP client can communicate to the server that it is using a certain type of hardware or firmware is to set a value in its DHCP requests called the Vendor Class Identifier (VCI) (Option 60).
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The value to which this option is set gives the DHCP server a hint about any required extra information that this client needs in a DHCP response.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Some types of set-top boxes set the VCI to inform the DHCP server about the hardware type and functionality of the device.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] An Aruba campus wireless access point, for example, supplies value 'ArubaAP' as option 60 in its DHCPDISCOVER message.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The DHCP server can then augment its DHCPOFFER with an IP address of an Aruba wireless controller in option 43, so the access point knows where to register itself.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Setting a VCI by the client allows a DHCP server to differentiate between client machines and process the requests from them appropriately.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The relay agent information option (option 82) specifies container for attaching sub-options to DHCP requests transmitted between a DHCP relay and a DHCP server.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] In small networks, where only one IP subnet is being managed, DHCP clients communicate directly with DHCP servers.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] However, DHCP servers can also provide IP addresses for multiple subnets.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] In this case, a DHCP client that has not yet acquired an IP address cannot communicate directly with a DHCP server not on the same subnet, as the client's broadcast can only be received on its own subnet.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] In order to allow DHCP clients on subnets not directly served by DHCP servers to communicate with DHCP servers, DHCP relay agents can be installed on these subnets.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] A DHCP relay agent runs on a network device, capable of routing between the client's subnet and the subnet of the DHCP server.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The DHCP client broadcasts on the local link; the relay agent receives the broadcast and transmits it to one or more DHCP servers using unicast.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The IP addresses of the DHCP servers are manually configured in the relay agent.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The relay agent stores its own IP address, from the interface on which it has received the client's broadcast, in the *GIADDR* field of the DHCP packet.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The DHCP server uses the GIADDR-value to determine the subnet, and subsequently the corresponding address pool, from which to allocate an IP address.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] When the DHCP server replies to the client, it sends the reply to the GIADDR-address, again using unicast.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The relay agent then retransmits the response on the local network, using unicast (in most cases) to the newly reserved IP address, in an Ethernet frame directed to the client's MAC address.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The client should accept the packet as its own, even when that IP address is not yet set on the interface.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Directly after processing the packet, the client sets the IP address on its interface and is ready for regular IP communication, directly thereafter.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] If the client's implementation of the IP stack does not accept unicast packets when it has no IP address yet, the client may set the *broadcast* bit in the FLAGS field when sending a DHCPDISCOVER packet.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The relay agent will use the *255.255.255.255* broadcast IP address (and the clients MAC address) to inform the client of the server's DHCPOFFER.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The communication between the relay agent and the DHCP server typically uses both a source and destination UDP port of 67.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The client moves through DHCP states depending on how the server responds to the messages that the client sends.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The DHCP ensures reliability in several ways: periodic renewal, rebinding, and failover.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] DHCP clients are allocated leases that last for some period of time.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Clients begin to attempt to renew their leases once half the lease interval has expired.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] They do this by sending a unicast *DHCPREQUEST* message to the DHCP server that granted the original lease.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] If that server is down or unreachable, it will fail to respond to the *DHCPREQUEST*.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] However, in that case the client repeats the *DHCPREQUEST* from time to time, so if the DHCP server comes back up or becomes reachable again, the DHCP client will succeed in contacting it and renew the lease.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] If the DHCP server is unreachable for an extended period of time, the DHCP client will attempt to rebind, by broadcasting its *DHCPREQUEST* rather than unicasting it.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Because it is broadcast, the *DHCPREQUEST* message will reach all available DHCP servers.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] If some other DHCP server is able to renew the lease, it will do so at this time.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] In order for rebinding to work, when the client successfully contacts a backup DHCP server, that server must have accurate information about the client's binding.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Maintaining accurate binding information between two servers is a complicated problem; if both servers are able to update the same lease database, there must be a mechanism to avoid conflicts between updates on the independent servers.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] A proposal for implementing fault-tolerant DHCP servers was submitted to the Internet Engineering Task Force, but never formalized.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] If rebinding fails, the lease will eventually expire.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] When the lease expires, the client must stop using the IP address granted to it in its lease.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] At that time it will restart the DHCP process from the beginning by broadcasting a `DHCPDISCOVER` message.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Since its lease has expired, it will accept any IP address offered to it.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Once it has a new IP address (presumably from a different DHCP server) it will once again be able to use the network.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] However, since its IP address has changed, any ongoing connections will be broken.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The basic methodology of DHCP was developed for networks based on Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4).
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Since the development and deployment of IPv6 networks, DHCP has also been used for assigning parameters in such networks, despite the inherent features of IPv6 for stateless address autoconfiguration.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The IPv6 version of the protocol is designated as DHCPv6.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The base DHCP does not include any mechanism for authentication.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Because of this, it is vulnerable to a variety of attacks.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Because the client has no way to validate the identity of a DHCP server, unauthorized DHCP servers (commonly called "rogue DHCP") can be operated on networks, providing incorrect information to DHCP clients.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] This can serve either as a denial-of-service attack, preventing the client from gaining access to network connectivity, or as a man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Because the DHCP server provides the DHCP client with server IP addresses, such as the IP address of one or more DNS servers, an attacker can convince a DHCP client to do its DNS lookups through its own DNS server, and can therefore provide its own answers to DNS queries from the client.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] This in turn allows the attacker to redirect network traffic through itself, allowing it to eavesdrop on connections between the client and network servers it contacts, or to simply replace those network servers with its own.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Because the DHCP server has no secure mechanism for authenticating the client, clients can gain unauthorized access to IP addresses by presenting credentials, such as client identifiers, that belong to other DHCP clients.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] This also allows DHCP clients to exhaust the DHCP server's store of IP addresses—by presenting new credentials each time it asks for an address, the client can consume all the available IP addresses on a particular network link, preventing other DHCP clients from getting service.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] DHCP does provide some mechanisms for mitigating these problems.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The Relay Agent Information Option protocol extension (usually referred to in the industry by its actual number as *Option 82*) allows network operators to attach tags to DHCP messages as these messages arrive on the network operator's trusted network.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] This tag is then used as an authorization token to control the client's access to network resources.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Because the client has no access to the network upstream of the relay agent, the lack of authentication does not prevent the DHCP server operator from relying on the authorization token.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Another extension, Authentication for DHCP Messages (RFC 3118), provides a mechanism for authenticating DHCP messages.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] As of 2002, this extension had not seen widespread adoption because of the problems of managing keys for large numbers of DHCP clients.
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Architectural proposals from 2008 involve authenticating DHCP requests using 802.1X or PANA (both of which transport EAP).
[src:networking/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] An IETF proposal was made for including EAP in DHCP itself, the so-called EAPoDHCP; this does not appear to have progressed beyond IETF draft level, the last of which dates to 2010.
[src:networking/https] The principal motivations for HTTPS are authentication of the accessed website and protection of the privacy and integrity of the exchanged data while it is in transit.
[src:networking/https] It protects against man-in-the-middle attacks, and the bidirectional block cipher encryption of communications between a client and server protects the communications against eavesdropping and tampering.
[src:networking/https] The authentication aspect of HTTPS requires a trusted third party to sign server-side digital certificates.
[src:networking/https] This was historically an expensive operation, which meant fully authenticated HTTPS connections were usually found only on secured payment transaction services and other secured corporate information systems on the World Wide Web.
[src:networking/https] In 2016, a campaign by the Electronic Frontier Foundation with the support of web browser developers led to the protocol becoming more prevalent.
[src:networking/https] HTTPS has since 2018 been used more often by web users than non-secure HTTP, primarily to protect page authenticity on all types of websites, secure accounts, and keep user communications, identity, and web browsing private.
[src:networking/https] The Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) scheme *HTTPS* has identical usage syntax to the HTTP scheme.
[src:networking/https] However, HTTPS signals the browser to use an added encryption layer of SSL/TLS to protect the traffic.
[src:networking/https] SSL/TLS is especially suited for HTTP, since it can provide some protection even if only one side of the communication is authenticated.
[src:networking/https] This is the case with HTTP transactions over the Internet, where typically only the server is authenticated (by the client examining the server's certificate).
[src:networking/https] HTTPS creates a secure channel over an insecure network.
[src:networking/https] This ensures reasonable protection from eavesdroppers and man-in-the-middle attacks, provided that adequate cipher suites are used and that the server certificate is verified and trusted.
[src:networking/https] Because HTTPS piggybacks HTTP entirely on top of TLS, the entirety of the underlying HTTP protocol can be encrypted.
[src:networking/https] This includes the request's URL, query parameters, headers, and cookies (which often contain identifying information about the user).
[src:networking/https] However, because website addresses and port numbers are necessarily part of the underlying TCP/IP protocols, HTTPS cannot protect their disclosure.
[src:networking/https] Web browsers know how to trust HTTPS websites based on certificate authorities that come pre-installed in their software.
[src:networking/https] Certificate authorities are in this way being trusted by web browser creators to provide valid certificates.
[src:networking/https] HTTPS is especially important over insecure networks and networks that may be subject to tampering.
[src:networking/https] Insecure networks, such as public Wi-Fi access points, allow anyone on the same local network to packet-sniff and discover sensitive information not protected by HTTPS.
[src:networking/https] Additionally, some free-to-use and paid WLAN networks have been observed tampering with webpages by engaging in packet injection in order to serve their own ads on other websites.
[src:networking/https] This practice can be exploited maliciously in many ways, such as by injecting malware onto webpages and stealing users' private information.
[src:networking/https] HTTPS is also important for connections over the Tor network, as malicious Tor nodes could otherwise damage or alter the contents passing through them in an insecure fashion and inject malware into the connection.
[src:networking/https] This is one reason why the Electronic Frontier Foundation and the Tor Project started the development of HTTPS Everywhere, which is included in Tor Browser.
[src:networking/https] As more information is revealed about global mass surveillance and criminals stealing personal information, the use of HTTPS security on all websites is becoming increasingly important regardless of the type of Internet connection being used.
[src:networking/https] Even though metadata about individual pages that a user visits might not be considered sensitive, when aggregated it can reveal a lot about the user and compromise the user's privacy.
[src:networking/https] Deploying HTTPS also allows the use of HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 (and their predecessors SPDY and QUIC), which are new HTTP versions designed to reduce page load times, size, and latency.
[src:networking/https] It is recommended to use HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS) with HTTPS to protect users from man-in-the-middle attacks, especially SSL stripping.
[src:networking/https] HTTPS should not be confused with the seldom-used Secure HTTP (S-HTTP) specified in RFC 2660.
[src:networking/https] As of April 2018, 33.2% of Alexa top 1,000,000 websites use HTTPS as default and 70% of page loads (measured by Firefox Telemetry) use HTTPS.
[src:networking/https] As of June 2025, 71.2% of the Internet's 150,000 most popular websites have a secure implementation of HTTPS (up from 58.4% in December 2022), However, despite TLS 1.3's release in 2018, adoption has been slow, with many still remaining on the older TLS 1.2 protocol.
[src:networking/https] Most browsers display a warning if they receive an invalid certificate.
[src:networking/https] Older browsers, when connecting to a site with an invalid certificate, would present the user with a dialog box asking whether they wanted to continue.
[src:networking/https] Newer browsers display a warning across the entire window.
[src:networking/https] Newer browsers also prominently display the site's security information in the address bar.
[src:networking/https] Extended validation certificates show the legal entity on the certificate information.
[src:networking/https] Most browsers also display a warning to the user when visiting a site that contains a mixture of encrypted and unencrypted content.
[src:networking/https] Additionally, many web filters return a security warning when visiting prohibited websites.
[src:networking/https] The Electronic Frontier Foundation, opining that "In an ideal world, every web request could be defaulted to HTTPS", has provided an add-on called HTTPS Everywhere for Mozilla Firefox, Google Chrome, Chromium, and Android, which enables HTTPS by default for hundreds of frequently used websites.
[src:networking/https] Forcing a web browser to load only HTTPS content has been supported in Firefox starting in version 83.
[src:networking/https] Starting in version 94, Google Chrome is able to "always use secure connections" if toggled in the browser's settings.
[src:networking/https] Prior to version 117, Google Chrome displayed a lock icon in the address bar, which has since been replaced by a "tune" icon.
[src:networking/https] Many users believe that a lock icon implies a website is safe, ignoring other security concerns.
[src:networking/https] The security of HTTPS is that of the underlying TLS, which typically uses long-term public and private keys to generate a short-term session key, which is then used to encrypt the data flow between the client and the server.
[src:networking/https] X.509 certificates are used to authenticate the server (and sometimes the client as well).
[src:networking/https] As a consequence, certificate authorities and public key certificates are necessary to verify the relation between the certificate and its owner, as well as to generate, sign, and administer the validity of certificates.
[src:networking/https] While this can be more beneficial than verifying the identities via a web of trust, the 2013 mass surveillance disclosures drew attention to certificate authorities as a potential weak point allowing man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:networking/https] An important property in this context is forward secrecy, which ensures that encrypted communications recorded in the past cannot be retrieved and decrypted should long-term secret keys or passwords be compromised in the future.
[src:networking/https] Not all web servers provide forward secrecy.
[src:networking/https] For HTTPS to be effective, a site must be completely hosted over HTTPS.
[src:networking/https] Additionally, cookies on a site served through HTTPS must have the secure attribute enabled.
[src:networking/https] On a site that has sensitive information on it, the user and the session will get exposed every time that site is accessed with HTTP instead of HTTPS.
[src:networking/https] HTTPS URLs begin with "https://" and use port 443 by default, whereas HTTP URLs begin with "http://" and use port 80 by default.
[src:networking/https] HTTP is not encrypted and thus is vulnerable to man-in-the-middle and eavesdropping attacks, which can let attackers gain access to website accounts and sensitive information, and modify webpages to inject malware or advertisements.
[src:networking/https] HTTPS is designed to withstand such attacks and is considered secure against them (with the exception of HTTPS implementations that use deprecated versions of SSL).
[src:networking/https] HTTP operates at the highest layer of the TCP/IP model—the application layer; as does the TLS security protocol (operating as a lower sublayer of the same layer), which encrypts an HTTP message prior to transmission and decrypts a message upon arrival.
[src:networking/https] Strictly speaking, HTTPS is not a separate protocol, but refers to the use of ordinary HTTP over an encrypted SSL/TLS connection.
[src:networking/https] HTTPS encrypts all message contents, including the HTTP headers and the request/response data.
[src:networking/https] With the exception of the possible CCA cryptographic attack described in the limitations section below, an attacker should at most be able to discover that a connection is taking place between two parties, along with their domain names and IP addresses.
[src:networking/https] To prepare a web server to accept HTTPS connections, the administrator must create a public key certificate for the web server.
[src:networking/https] This certificate must be signed by a trusted certificate authority for the web browser to accept it without warning.
[src:networking/https] The authority certifies that the certificate holder is the operator of the web server that presents it.
[src:networking/https] Web browsers are generally distributed with a list of signing certificates of major certificate authorities so that they can verify certificates signed by them.
[src:networking/https] A number of commercial certificate authorities exist, offering paid-for SSL/TLS certificates of a number of types, including Extended Validation Certificates.
[src:networking/https] Let's Encrypt, launched in April 2016, provides free and automated service that delivers basic SSL/TLS certificates to websites.
[src:networking/https] According to the Electronic Frontier Foundation, Let's Encrypt will make switching from HTTP to HTTPS "as easy as issuing one command, or clicking one button." The majority of web hosts and cloud providers now leverage Let's Encrypt, providing free certificates to their customers.
[src:networking/https] The system can also be used for client authentication in order to limit access to a web server to authorized users.
[src:networking/https] To do this, the site administrator typically creates a certificate for each user, which the user loads into their browser.
[src:networking/https] Normally, the certificate contains the name and e-mail address of the authorized user and is automatically checked by the server on each connection to verify the user's identity, potentially without even requiring a password.
[src:networking/https] An important property in this context is perfect forward secrecy (PFS).
[src:networking/https] Possessing one of the long-term asymmetric secret keys used to establish an HTTPS session should not make it easier to derive the short-term session key to then decrypt the conversation, even at a later time.
[src:networking/https] Diffie–Hellman key exchange (DHE) and Elliptic-curve Diffie–Hellman key exchange (ECDHE) are in 2013 the only schemes known to have that property.
[src:networking/https] In 2013, only 30% of Firefox, Opera, and Chromium Browser sessions used it, and nearly 0% of Apple's Safari and Microsoft Internet Explorer sessions.
[src:networking/https] TLS 1.3, published in August 2018, dropped support for ciphers without forward secrecy.
[src:networking/https] As of February 2019, 96.6% of web servers surveyed support some form of forward secrecy, and 52.1% will use forward secrecy with most browsers.
[src:networking/https] As of July 2023, 99.6% of web servers surveyed support some form of forward secrecy, and 75.2% will use forward secrecy with most browsers.
[src:networking/https] A certificate may be revoked before it expires, for example because the secrecy of the private key has been compromised.
[src:networking/https] Newer versions of popular browsers such as Firefox, Opera, and Internet Explorer on Windows Vista implement the Online Certificate Status Protocol (OCSP) to verify that this is not the case.
[src:networking/https] The browser sends the certificate's serial number to the certificate authority or its delegate via OCSP (Online Certificate Status Protocol) and the authority responds, telling the browser whether the certificate is still valid or not.
[src:networking/https] The CA may also issue a CRL to tell people that these certificates are revoked.
[src:networking/https] CRLs are no longer required by the CA/Browser forum, nevertheless, they are still widely used by the CAs.
[src:networking/https] Most revocation statuses on the Internet disappear soon after the expiration of the certificates.
[src:networking/https] SSL (Secure Sockets Layer) and TLS (Transport Layer Security) encryption can be configured in two modes: *simple* and *mutual*.
[src:networking/https] In simple mode, authentication is only performed by the server.
[src:networking/https] The mutual version requires the user to install a personal client certificate in the web browser for user authentication.
[src:networking/https] In either case, the level of protection depends on the correctness of the implementation of the software and the cryptographic algorithms in use.
[src:networking/https] SSL/TLS does not prevent the indexing of the site by a web crawler, and in some cases the URI of the encrypted resource can be inferred by knowing only the intercepted request/response size.
[src:networking/https] This allows an attacker to have access to the plaintext (the publicly available static content), and the encrypted text (the encrypted version of the static content), permitting a cryptographic attack.
[src:networking/https] Because TLS operates at a protocol level below that of HTTP and has no knowledge of the higher-level protocols, TLS servers can only strictly present one certificate for a particular address and port combination.
[src:networking/https] In the past, this meant that it was not feasible to use name-based virtual hosting with HTTPS.
[src:networking/https] A solution called Server Name Indication (SNI) exists, which sends the hostname to the server before encrypting the connection, although older browsers do not support this extension.
[src:networking/https] Support for SNI is available since Firefox 2, Opera 8, Apple Safari 2.1, Google Chrome 6, and Internet Explorer 7 on Windows Vista.
[src:networking/https] A sophisticated type of man-in-the-middle attack called SSL stripping was presented at the 2009 Blackhat Conference.
[src:networking/https] The attacker then communicates in clear with the client.
[src:networking/https] This prompted the development of a countermeasure in HTTP called HTTP Strict Transport Security.
[src:networking/https] HTTPS has been shown to be vulnerable to a range of traffic analysis attacks.
[src:networking/https] Traffic analysis attacks are a type of side-channel attack that relies on variations in the timing and size of traffic in order to infer properties about the encrypted traffic itself.
[src:networking/https] Traffic analysis is possible because SSL/TLS encryption changes the contents of traffic, but has minimal impact on the size and timing of traffic.
[src:networking/https] In May 2010, a research paper by researchers from Microsoft Research and Indiana University discovered that detailed sensitive user data can be inferred from side channels such as packet sizes.
[src:networking/https] The researchers found that, despite HTTPS protection in several high-profile, top-of-the-line web applications in healthcare, taxation, investment, and web search, an eavesdropper could infer the illnesses/medications/surgeries of the user, his/her family income, and investment secrets.
[src:networking/https] The fact that most modern websites, including Google, Yahoo!, and Amazon, use HTTPS causes problems for many users trying to access public Wi-Fi hot spots, because a captive portal Wi-Fi hot spot login page fails to load if the user tries to open an HTTPS resource.
[src:networking/https] Several websites, such as NoSSL.sh, guarantee that they will always remain accessible by HTTP.
[src:networking/https] Netscape Communications created HTTPS in 1994 for its Netscape Navigator web browser.
[src:networking/https] Originally, HTTPS was used with the SSL protocol.
[src:networking/https] The original SSL protocol was developed by Taher Elgamal, chief scientist at Netscape Communications.
[src:networking/https] As SSL evolved into Transport Layer Security (TLS), HTTPS was formally specified by RFC 2818 in May 2000.
[src:networking/https] Google announced in February 2018 that its Chrome browser would mark HTTP sites as "Not Secure" after July 2018.
[src:networking/https] This move was to encourage website owners to implement HTTPS, as an effort to make the World Wide Web more secure.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] The **Internet Protocol** (**IP**) is the network layer communications protocol in the Internet protocol suite for relaying datagrams across network boundaries.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] Its routing function enables internetworking, and essentially establishes the Internet.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] IP has the task of delivering packets from the source host to the destination host solely based on the IP addresses in the packet headers.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] For this purpose, IP defines packet structures that encapsulate the data to be delivered.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] It also defines addressing methods that are used to label the datagram with source and destination information.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] IP was the connectionless datagram service in the original *Transmission Control Program* introduced by Vint Cerf and Bob Kahn in 1974, which was complemented by a connection-oriented service that became the basis for the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:networking/internet-protocol] The Internet protocol suite is therefore often referred to as *TCP/IP*.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] The first major version of IP, Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4), is the dominant protocol of the Internet.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] Its successor is Internet Protocol version 6 (IPv6), which has been in increasing deployment on the public Internet since around 2006.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] The Internet Protocol is responsible for addressing host interfaces, encapsulating data into datagrams (including fragmentation and reassembly) and routing datagrams from a source host interface to a destination host interface across one or more IP networks.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] For these purposes, the Internet Protocol defines the format of packets and provides an addressing system.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] Each datagram has two components: a header and a payload.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] The IP header includes a source IP address, a destination IP address, and other metadata needed to route and deliver the datagram.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] The payload is the data that is transported.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] This method of nesting the data payload in a packet with a header is called encapsulation.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] IP addressing entails the assignment of IP addresses and associated parameters to host interfaces.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] The address space is divided into subnets, involving the designation of network prefixes.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] IP routing is performed by all hosts, as well as routers, whose main function is to transport packets across network boundaries.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] Routers communicate with one another via specially designed routing protocols, either interior gateway protocols or exterior gateway protocols, as needed for the topology of the network.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] In May 1974, the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) published a paper entitled "A Protocol for Packet Network Intercommunication".
[src:networking/internet-protocol] The paper's authors, Vint Cerf and Bob Kahn, described an internetworking protocol for sharing resources using packet switching among network nodes.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] A central control component of this model was the Transmission Control Program that incorporated both connection-oriented links and datagram services between hosts.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] The monolithic Transmission Control Program was later divided into a modular architecture consisting of the Transmission Control Protocol and User Datagram Protocol at the transport layer and the Internet Protocol at the internet layer.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] The model became known as the *Department of Defense (DoD) Internet Model* and *Internet protocol suite*, and informally as *TCP/IP*.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] IP versions 1 to 3 were experimental versions, designed between 1973 and 1978.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] Versions 2 and 3 supported variable-length addresses ranging between 1 and 16 octets (between 8 and 128 bits).
[src:networking/internet-protocol] An early draft of version 4 supported variable-length addresses of up to 256 octets (up to 2048 bits) but this was later abandoned in favor of a fixed-size 32-bit address in the final version of IPv4.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] This remains the dominant internetworking protocol in use in the Internet Layer; the number 4 identifies the protocol version, carried in every IP datagram.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] Version number 5 was used by the Internet Stream Protocol, an experimental streaming protocol that was not adopted.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] IPv6 was a result of several years of experimentation and dialog during which various protocol models were proposed, such as TP/IX (RFC 1475), PIP (RFC 1621) and TUBA (TCP and UDP with Bigger Addresses, RFC 1347).
[src:networking/internet-protocol] Its most prominent difference from version 4 is the size of the addresses.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] While IPv4 uses 32 bits for addressing, yielding c.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] 4.3 billion (4.3×109) addresses, IPv6 uses 128-bit addresses providing c.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] Although adoption of IPv6 has been slow, as of January 2023, most countries in the world show significant adoption of IPv6, with over 41% of Google's traffic being carried over IPv6 connections.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] The assignment of the new protocol as IPv6 was uncertain until due diligence assured that IPv6 had not been used previously.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] Other Internet Layer protocols have been assigned version numbers, such as 7 (*IP/TX*), 8 and 9 (*historic*).
[src:networking/internet-protocol] Notably, on April 1, 1994, the IETF published an April Fools' Day RfC about IPv9.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] IPv9 was also used in an alternate proposed address space expansion called TUBA.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] A 2004 Chinese proposal for an IPv9 protocol appears to be unrelated to all of these, and is not endorsed by the IETF.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] As the version number is carried in a four-bit field, only numbers 0–15 can be assigned.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] The design of the Internet protocol suite adheres to the end-to-end principle, a concept adapted from the CYCLADES project.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] Under the end-to-end principle, the network infrastructure is considered inherently unreliable at any single network element or transmission medium and is dynamic in terms of the availability of links and nodes.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] No central monitoring or performance measurement facility exists that tracks or maintains the state of the network.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] For the benefit of reducing network complexity, the intelligence in the network is located in the end nodes.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] As a consequence of this design, the Internet Protocol only provides best-effort delivery and its service is characterized as unreliable.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] In network architectural parlance, it is a connectionless protocol, in contrast to connection-oriented communication.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] Various fault conditions may occur, such as data corruption, packet loss and duplication.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] Because routing is dynamic, meaning every packet is treated independently, and because the network maintains no state based on the path of prior packets, different packets may be routed to the same destination via different paths, resulting in out-of-order delivery to the receiver.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] All fault conditions in the network must be detected and compensated for by the participating end nodes.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] The upper layer protocols of the Internet protocol suite are responsible for resolving reliability issues.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] For example, a host may buffer network data to ensure correct ordering before the data is delivered to an application.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] IPv4 provides safeguards to ensure that the header of an IP packet is error-free.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] A routing node discards packets that fail a header checksum test.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] Although the Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) provides notification of errors, a routing node is not required to notify either end node of errors.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] IPv6, by contrast, operates without header checksums, since current link layer technology is assumed to provide sufficient error detection.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] The dynamic nature of the Internet and the diversity of its components provide no guarantee that any particular path is actually capable of, or suitable for, performing the data transmission requested.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] One of the technical constraints is the size of data packets possible on a given link.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] Facilities exist to examine the maximum transmission unit (MTU) size of the local link and Path MTU Discovery can be used for the entire intended path to the destination.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] The IPv4 internetworking layer automatically fragments a datagram into smaller units for transmission when the link MTU is exceeded.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] IP provides re-ordering of fragments received out of order.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] An IPv6 network does not perform fragmentation in network elements, but requires end hosts and higher-layer protocols to avoid exceeding the path MTU.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] The Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) is an example of a protocol that adjusts its segment size to be smaller than the MTU.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] The User Datagram Protocol (UDP) and ICMP disregard MTU size, thereby forcing IP to fragment oversized datagrams.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] During the design phase of the ARPANET and the early Internet, the security aspects and needs of a public, international network were not adequately anticipated.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] Consequently, many Internet protocols exhibited vulnerabilities highlighted by network attacks and later security assessments.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] In 2008, a thorough security assessment and proposed mitigation of problems was published.
[src:networking/internet-protocol] The IETF has been pursuing further studies.
[src:networking/ip-address] An **Internet Protocol address** (**IP address**) is a numerical label, such as *192.168.1.1* or *2001:0db8:0000:0000:0000:8a2e:0370:7334*, that is assigned to a device connected to a computer network that uses the Internet Protocol for communication.
[src:networking/ip-address] IP addresses serve two main functions: network interface identification, and location addressing.
[src:networking/ip-address] Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4) was the first standalone specification for the IP address, and has been in use since 1983.
[src:networking/ip-address] IPv4 addresses are defined as a 32-bit number, which later then became too small to provide enough addresses as the internet grew, leading to IPv4 address exhaustion over the 2010s.
[src:networking/ip-address] Its designated successor, IPv6, uses 128 bits for the IP address, giving it a larger address space.
[src:networking/ip-address] Although IPv6 deployment has been ongoing since the mid-2000s, both IPv4 and IPv6 are still used side-by-side as of 2025.
[src:networking/ip-address] IP addresses are usually displayed in a human-readable notation, but systems may use them in various different computer number formats.
[src:networking/ip-address] CIDR notation can also be used to designate how much of the address should be treated as a routing prefix.
[src:networking/ip-address] For example, *192.0.2.1/24* indicates that 24 significant bits of the address are the prefix, with the remaining 8 bits used for host addressing.
[src:networking/ip-address] This is equivalent to the historically used subnet mask (in this case, *255.255.255.0*).
[src:networking/ip-address] The IP address space is managed globally by the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA) and the five regional Internet registries (RIRs).
[src:networking/ip-address] IANA assigns blocks of IP addresses to the RIRs, which are responsible for distributing them to local Internet registries in their region, such as internet service providers (ISPs) and large institutions.
[src:networking/ip-address] Some addresses are reserved for private networks and are not globally unique.
[src:networking/ip-address] Within a network, the network administrator assigns an IP address to each device.
[src:networking/ip-address] Such assignments may be on a *static* (fixed or permanent) or *dynamic* basis, depending on network practices and software features.
[src:networking/ip-address] Some jurisdictions, such as Canada and the European Union, consider IP addresses to be personal data.
[src:networking/ip-address] An IP address serves two principal functions: it identifies the host, or more specifically, its network interface, and it provides the location of the host in the network, and thus, the capability of establishing a path to that host.
[src:networking/ip-address] Its role has been characterized as follows: "A name indicates what we seek.
[src:networking/ip-address] A route indicates how to get there." The header of each IP packet contains the IP address of the sending host and that of the destination host.
[src:networking/ip-address] Two versions of the Internet Protocol are in common use on the Internet today.
[src:networking/ip-address] The original version of the Internet Protocol that was first deployed in 1983 in the ARPANET, the predecessor of the Internet, is Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4).
[src:networking/ip-address] By the early 1990s, the rapid exhaustion of IPv4 address space available for assignment to Internet service providers and end-user organizations prompted the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) to explore new technologies to expand addressing capability on the Internet.
[src:networking/ip-address] The result was a redesign of the Internet Protocol, which eventually became known as Internet Protocol Version 6 (IPv6) in 1995.
[src:networking/ip-address] IPv6 technology was in various testing stages until the mid-2000s, when commercial production deployment commenced.
[src:networking/ip-address] Today, these two versions of the Internet Protocol are in simultaneous use.
[src:networking/ip-address] Among other technical changes, each version defines the format of addresses differently.
[src:networking/ip-address] Because of the historical prevalence of IPv4, the generic term *IP address* typically still refers to the addresses defined by IPv4.
[src:networking/ip-address] The gap in version sequence between IPv4 and IPv6 resulted from the assignment of version 5 to the experimental Internet Stream Protocol in 1979, which, however, was never referred to as *IPv5*.
[src:networking/ip-address] Versions 1 to 9 were defined, but only 4 and 6 ever gained widespread use.
[src:networking/ip-address] Transmission Control Protocol (the protocol suite later referred to as *TCP/IP*) versions 1 and 2 were published in 1974 and 1977.
[src:networking/ip-address] Version 3 was defined in 1978, and version 3.1 is the first version in which TCP is separated from IP.
[src:networking/ip-address] Version 6 is a synthesis of several suggested versions, version 6 *Simple Internet Protocol*, version 7 *TP/IX: The Next Internet*, version 8 *P.
[src:networking/ip-address] Internet Protocol*, and version 9 *TCP and UDP with Bigger Addresses (TUBA)*.
[src:networking/ip-address] IP networks may be divided into subnetworks in both IPv4 and IPv6.
[src:networking/ip-address] For this purpose, an IP address is recognized as consisting of two parts: the *network prefix* in the high-order bits and the remaining bits called the *rest field*, *host identifier*, or *interface identifier* (IPv6), used for host numbering within a network.
[src:networking/ip-address] The subnet mask or CIDR notation determines how the IP address is divided into network and host parts.
[src:networking/ip-address] The term *subnet mask* is only used within IPv4.
[src:networking/ip-address] Both IP versions, however, use the CIDR concept and notation.
[src:networking/ip-address] In this, the IP address is followed by a slash and the number (in decimal) of bits used for the network part, also called the *routing prefix*.
[src:networking/ip-address] The CIDR notation for the same IP address and subnet is *192.0.2.1/24*, because the first 24 bits of the IP address indicate the network and subnet.
[src:networking/ip-address] An IPv4 address has a size of 32 bits, which limits the address space to 4294967296 (232) addresses.
[src:networking/ip-address] Of this number, some addresses are reserved for special purposes such as private networks (≈18 million addresses) and multicast addressing (≈270 million addresses).
[src:networking/ip-address] IPv4 addresses are usually represented in dot-decimal notation, consisting of four decimal numbers, each ranging from 0 to 255, separated by dots, e.g., *192.0.2.1*.
[src:networking/ip-address] Each part represents a group of 8 bits (an octet) of the address.
[src:networking/ip-address] In some cases of technical writing, IPv4 addresses may be presented in various hexadecimal, octal, or binary representations.
[src:networking/ip-address] In the early stages of development of the Internet Protocol, the network number was always the highest-order octet (most significant eight bits).
[src:networking/ip-address] Because this method allowed for only 256 networks, it soon proved inadequate as additional networks developed that were independent of the existing networks already designated by a network number.
[src:networking/ip-address] In 1981, the addressing specification was revised with the introduction of classful network architecture.
[src:networking/ip-address] Classful network design allowed for a larger number of individual network assignments and fine-grained subnetwork design.
[src:networking/ip-address] The first three bits of the most significant octet of an IP address were defined as the *class* of the address.
[src:networking/ip-address] Three classes (*A*, *B*, and *C*) were defined for universal unicast addressing.
[src:networking/ip-address] Depending on the class derived, the network identification was based on octet boundary segments of the entire address.
[src:networking/ip-address] Each class used successively additional octets in the network identifier, thus reducing the possible number of hosts in the higher-order classes (*B* and *C*).
[src:networking/ip-address] The following table gives an overview of this now-obsolete system.
[src:networking/ip-address] Classful network design served its purpose in the startup stage of the Internet, but it lacked scalability in the face of the rapid expansion of networking in the 1990s.
[src:networking/ip-address] The class system of the address space was replaced with Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR) in 1993.
[src:networking/ip-address] CIDR is based on variable-length subnet masking (VLSM) to allow allocation and routing based on arbitrary-length prefixes.
[src:networking/ip-address] Today, remnants of classful network concepts function only in a limited scope as the default configuration parameters of some network software and hardware components (e.g. netmask), and in the technical jargon used in network administrators' discussions.
[src:networking/ip-address] Early network design, when global end-to-end connectivity was envisioned for communications with all Internet hosts, intended that IP addresses be globally unique.
[src:networking/ip-address] However, it was found that this was not always necessary as private networks developed and public address space needed to be conserved.
[src:networking/ip-address] Computers not connected to the Internet, such as factory machines that communicate only with each other via TCP/IP, need not have globally unique IP addresses.
[src:networking/ip-address] Today, such private networks are widely used and typically connect to the Internet with network address translation (NAT), when needed.
[src:networking/ip-address] Three non-overlapping ranges of IPv4 addresses for private networks are reserved.
[src:networking/ip-address] These addresses are not routed on the Internet, and thus their use need not be coordinated with an IP address registry.
[src:networking/ip-address] Any user may use any of the reserved blocks.
[src:networking/ip-address] Typically, a network administrator will divide a block into subnets; for example, many home routers automatically use a default address range of *192.168.0.0* through *192.168.0.255* (*192.168.0.0/24*).
[src:networking/ip-address] In IPv6, the address size was increased from 32 bits in IPv4 to 128 bits, thus providing up to 2128 (approximately 3.403×1038) addresses.
[src:networking/ip-address] This is deemed sufficient for the foreseeable future.
[src:networking/ip-address] The intent of the new design was not to provide just a sufficient quantity of addresses, but also to redesign routing in the Internet by allowing more efficient aggregation of subnetwork routing prefixes.
[src:networking/ip-address] This resulted in slower growth of routing tables in routers.
[src:networking/ip-address] The smallest possible individual allocation is a subnet for 264 hosts, which is the square of the size of the entire IPv4 Internet.
[src:networking/ip-address] At these levels, actual address utilization ratios will be small on any IPv6 network segment.
[src:networking/ip-address] The new design also provides the opportunity to separate the addressing infrastructure of a network segment, i.e., the local administration of the segment's available space, from the addressing prefix used to route traffic to and from external networks.
[src:networking/ip-address] IPv6 has facilities that automatically change the routing prefix of entire networks, should the global connectivity or the routing policy change, without requiring internal redesign or manual renumbering.
[src:networking/ip-address] The large number of IPv6 addresses allows large blocks to be assigned for specific purposes and, where appropriate, to be aggregated for efficient routing.
[src:networking/ip-address] With a large address space, there is no need to have complex address conservation methods as used in CIDR.
[src:networking/ip-address] All modern desktop and enterprise server operating systems include native support for IPv6, but it is not yet widely deployed in other devices, such as residential networking routers, voice over IP (VoIP) and multimedia equipment, and some networking hardware.
[src:networking/ip-address] Just as IPv4 reserves addresses for private networks, blocks of addresses are set aside in IPv6.
[src:networking/ip-address] In IPv6, these are referred to as unique local addresses (ULAs).
[src:networking/ip-address] The routing prefix *fc00::/7* is reserved for this block, which is divided into two */8* blocks with different implied policies.
[src:networking/ip-address] The addresses include a 40-bit pseudorandom number that minimizes the risk of address collisions if sites merge or packets are misrouted.
[src:networking/ip-address] Early practices used a different block for this purpose (*fec0::*), dubbed site-local addresses.
[src:networking/ip-address] However, the definition of what constituted a *site* remained unclear and the poorly defined addressing policy created ambiguities for routing.
[src:networking/ip-address] This address type was abandoned and must not be used in new systems.
[src:networking/ip-address] Addresses starting with *fe80::*, called link-local addresses, are assigned to interfaces for communication on the attached link.
[src:networking/ip-address] The addresses are automatically generated by the operating system for each network interface.
[src:networking/ip-address] This provides instant and automatic communication between all IPv6 hosts on a link.
[src:networking/ip-address] This feature is used in the lower layers of IPv6 network administration, such as for the Neighbor Discovery Protocol.
[src:networking/ip-address] Private and link-local address prefixes may not be routed on the public Internet.
[src:networking/ip-address] IP addresses are assigned to a host either dynamically as they join the network, or persistently by configuration of the host hardware or software.
[src:networking/ip-address] Persistent configuration is also known as using a **static IP address**.
[src:networking/ip-address] In contrast, when a computer's IP address is assigned each time it restarts, this is known as using a **dynamic IP address**.
[src:networking/ip-address] Dynamic IP addresses are assigned by the network.
[src:networking/ip-address] Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) is the most frequently used technology for assigning addresses.
[src:networking/ip-address] It avoids the administrative burden of assigning specific static addresses to each device on a network.
[src:networking/ip-address] It also allows devices to share the limited address space on a network if only some of them are online at a particular time.
[src:networking/ip-address] Typically, dynamic IP configuration is enabled by default in modern desktop operating systems.
[src:networking/ip-address] The address assigned with DHCP is associated with a *lease* and usually has an expiration period.
[src:networking/ip-address] If the lease is not renewed by the host before expiry, the address may be assigned to another device.
[src:networking/ip-address] Some DHCP implementations attempt to reassign the same IP address to a host, based on its MAC address, each time it joins the network.
[src:networking/ip-address] A network administrator may configure a DHCP server to allocate specific IP addresses to specific MAC addresses.
[src:networking/ip-address] DHCP is not the only technology used to assign IP addresses dynamically.
[src:networking/ip-address] Bootstrap Protocol is a similar protocol and predecessor to DHCP.
[src:networking/ip-address] Dialup and some broadband networks use dynamic address features of the Point-to-Point Protocol.
[src:networking/ip-address] Computers and equipment used for the network infrastructure, such as routers and mail servers, are typically configured with static addressing.
[src:networking/ip-address] In the absence or failure of static or dynamic address configurations, an operating system may assign a link-local address to a host using stateless address autoconfiguration.
[src:networking/ip-address] Address block *169.254.0.0/16* is defined for the special use of link-local addressing for IPv4 networks.
[src:networking/ip-address] In IPv6, every interface, whether using static or dynamic addresses, also receives a link-local address automatically in the block *fe80::/10*.
[src:networking/ip-address] These addresses are only valid on the link, such as a local network segment or point-to-point connection, to which a host is connected.
[src:networking/ip-address] These addresses are not routable and, like private addresses, cannot be the source or destination of packets traversing the Internet.
[src:networking/ip-address] When the link-local IPv4 address block was reserved, no standards existed for mechanisms of address autoconfiguration.
[src:networking/ip-address] Filling the void, Microsoft developed a protocol called Automatic Private IP Addressing (APIPA), whose first public implementation appeared in Windows 98.
[src:networking/ip-address] APIPA has been deployed on millions of machines and became a *de facto* standard in the industry.
[src:networking/ip-address] In May 2005, the IETF defined a formal standard for it.
[src:networking/ip-address] An IP address conflict occurs when two devices on the same local physical or wireless network claim to have the same IP address.
[src:networking/ip-address] A second assignment of an address generally stops the IP functionality of one or both of the devices.
[src:networking/ip-address] Many modern operating systems notify the administrator of IP address conflicts.
[src:networking/ip-address] When IP addresses are assigned by multiple people and systems with differing methods, any of them may be at fault.
[src:networking/ip-address] If one of the devices involved in the conflict is the default gateway access beyond the LAN for all devices on the LAN, all devices may be impaired.
[src:networking/ip-address] IP addresses are classified into several classes of operational characteristics: unicast, multicast, anycast and broadcast addressing.
[src:networking/ip-address] The most common concept of an IP address is in unicast addressing, available in both IPv4 and IPv6.
[src:networking/ip-address] It normally refers to a single sender or a single receiver, and can be used for both sending and receiving.
[src:networking/ip-address] Usually, a unicast address is associated with a single device or host, but a device or host may have more than one unicast address.
[src:networking/ip-address] Sending the same data to multiple unicast addresses requires the sender to send all the data many times over, once for each recipient.
[src:networking/ip-address] Broadcasting is an addressing technique available in IPv4 to address data to all possible destinations on a network in one transmission operation as an *all-hosts broadcast*.
[src:networking/ip-address] All receivers capture the network packet.
[src:networking/ip-address] In addition, a more limited directed broadcast uses the all-ones host address with the network prefix.
[src:networking/ip-address] For example, the destination address used for directed broadcast to devices on the network *192.0.2.0/24* is *192.0.2.255*.
[src:networking/ip-address] IPv6 does not implement broadcast addressing and replaces it with multicast to the specially defined all-nodes multicast address.
[src:networking/ip-address] A multicast address is associated with a group of interested receivers.
[src:networking/ip-address] In IPv4, addresses *224.0.0.0* through *239.255.255.255* (the former Class D addresses) are designated as multicast addresses.
[src:networking/ip-address] IPv6 uses the address block with the prefix *ff00::/8* for multicast.
[src:networking/ip-address] In either case, the sender sends a single datagram from its unicast address to the multicast group address, and the intermediary routers take care of making copies and sending them to all interested receivers (those that have joined the corresponding multicast group).
[src:networking/ip-address] Like broadcast and multicast, anycast is a one-to-many routing topology.
[src:networking/ip-address] However, the data stream is not transmitted to all receivers, just the one that the router decides is closest in the network.
[src:networking/ip-address] Anycast addressing is a built-in feature of IPv6.
[src:networking/ip-address] In IPv4, anycast addressing is implemented with Border Gateway Protocol using the shortest-path metric to choose destinations.
[src:networking/ip-address] Anycast methods are useful for global load balancing and are commonly used in distributed DNS systems.
[src:networking/ip-address] A host may use geolocation to deduce the geographic position of its communicating peer.
[src:networking/ip-address] This is typically done by retrieving geolocation info about the IP address of the other node from a database.
[src:networking/ip-address] A public IP address is a globally routable unicast IP address, meaning that the address is not an address reserved for use in private networks, such as those reserved by RFC 1918, or the various IPv6 address formats of local scope or site-local scope, for example, for link-local addressing.
[src:networking/ip-address] Public IP addresses may be used for communication between hosts on the global Internet.
[src:networking/ip-address] In a home situation, a public IP address is the IP address assigned to the home's network by the ISP.
[src:networking/ip-address] In this case, it is also locally visible by logging into the router configuration.
[src:networking/ip-address] Most public IP addresses change relatively often.
[src:networking/ip-address] Any type of IP address that changes is called a dynamic IP address.
[src:networking/ip-address] In home networks, the ISP usually assigns a dynamic IP.
[src:networking/ip-address] If an ISP gave a home network an unchanging address, it is more likely to be abused by customers who host websites from home, or by hackers who can try the same IP address over and over until they breach a network.
[src:networking/ip-address] A common practice is to have a NAT device mask many devices in a private network.
[src:networking/ip-address] Only the public interfaces of the NAT device need to have an Internet-routable address.
[src:networking/ip-address] The NAT device maps different IP addresses on the private network to different TCP or UDP port numbers on the public network.
[src:networking/ip-address] In residential networks, NAT functions are usually implemented in a residential gateway.
[src:networking/ip-address] In this scenario, the computers connected to the router have private IP addresses, and the router has a public address on its external interface to communicate on the Internet.
[src:networking/ip-address] The internal computers appear to share one public IP address.
[src:networking/ip-address] In March 2024, the Supreme Court of Canada decided that the IP addresses are protected private information under the *Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms*, with police searches requiring a warrant in order to obtain them.
[src:networking/ip-address] IP addresses are considered personal data by the European Commission and are protected by the *General Data Protection Regulation*.
[src:networking/ip-address] In the United States, the California Consumer Privacy Act only protects IP addresses that link to any particular consumer or household; otherwise it is not private data and is not protected under American law.
[src:networking/ip-address] Computer operating systems provide various diagnostic tools to examine network interfaces and address configuration.
[src:networking/ip-address] Microsoft Windows provides the command-line interface tools ipconfig and netsh and users of Unix-like systems may use ifconfig, netstat, route, lanstat, fstat, and iproute2 utilities to accomplish the task.
